To compute the coefficient, start with

\begin{align*}f(t)=\sum_{n=-\infty }^{\infty }c_ne_n(t)\end{align*}

where $\displaystyle f(t)=t^2-t$ and
$\displaystyle e_n(t)=e^{2\pi int}$. Also, we have \emph{L=1-0=1}. Take
the inner product of \emph{$f$(t)} with $e_m$. The only term in the
infinite sum that remains is the one with $n=m$, and in this case
$\langle e_n, e_n\rangle = 1$. Thus

\begin{align*}\left \langle f,e_m \right \rangle=\sum_{n=-\infty }^{\infty }c_n\left \langle e_n,e_m \right \rangle=c_m\end{align*}

and we get the formula

\begin{align*}c_m = \langle f,e_m \rangle = \int_{0}^{1} f(t) e^{-2\pi imt}\,dt=\int_{0}^{1}f(t)\overline{g(t)}\,dt\end{align*}

Since $\displaystyle \overline{g(t)}=e^{-2\pi imt}$ we have
$\displaystyle g(t)=e^{2\pi imt}$, and so we overall find that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle c_n = \langle t^2-t, e^{2\pi int} \rangle\end{align*}
